##   Protecting your Zoom accounts and sensitive information

To help protect Zoom accounts and sensitive information you should:  

-   [use a strong and separate password](https://www.ncsc.gov.uk/collection/top-tips-for-staying-secure-online/use-a-strong-and-separate-password-for-email) for Zoom accounts 
-   enable [2 Factor Authentication](https://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/360038247071-Setting-up-and-using-two-factor-authentication) for your Zoom accounts
-   not share emails or open documents with your audience when screen sharing

## Hosting a Zoom meeting

As a Zoom meeting host, you should:  
  
-   use a centrally managed Zoom account issued by your organisation
-   always use the Zoom.us web client and not the Zoom desktop client application
-   not record Zoom meetings by default
-   never host a government meeting from an account not managed by your organisation
-   tailor your content to attendees, who might not have non-disclosure agreements and could make information public
-   stop any discussions that may contain information that is sensitive, which is to say conversations that would have damaging consequences for individuals, an organisation, or government generally, if released to the public  

## Scheduling a Zoom meeting  
  
When [scheduling a meeting](https://support.zoom.us/hc/en-us/articles/201362413-How-Do-I-Schedule-Meetings-) you should make sure it has:  
  
-   a title
-   a description
-   date and time - remember that Zoom displays the date in the US format by default (month-date-year)
-   a waiting room so the host can admit them into meetings
-   a passcode that is not in the calendar invite but that you share by email or another secure messaging platform
    
